04469nam a22007335i 9780813554501DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20132013nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2012009920  a97808135545017 a10.36019/97808135545012doi  a(DE-B1597)529721  a(OCoLC)1014477236  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aPN1996b.F4553 2012 7aPER0000002bisacsh04a791.43/6572231 aFischer, Lucy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBody Double :bThe Author Incarnate in the Cinema /cLucy Fischer. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b41 photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Screen Author — Wanted: Dead or Alive -- t1. Typecasting the Author -- t2. Beyond Adaptation: The Writer as Filmmaker -- t3. The Author at the Dream Factory: The Screenwriter and the Movies -- t4. The Authoress: Textuality as Sexuality -- t5. Writing Pain: The Infirm Author -- t6. Cinécriture: Word and Image -- t7. Corpus and Oeuvre: Authorship and the Body -- t8. Stealing Beauty: The Reader, the Critic, and the Appropriation of the Authorial Voice -- tAfterword: Signs and Meaning in the Cinema -- tNotes -- tFilmography -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBody Double explores the myriad ways that film artists have represented the creative process. In this highly innovative work, Lucy Fischer draws on a neglected element of auteur studies to show that filmmakers frequently raise questions about the paradoxes of authorship by portraying the onscreen writer. Dealing with such varied topics as the icon of the typewriter, the case of the writer/director, the authoress, and the omnipresent infirm author, she probes the ways in which films can tell a plausible story while contemplating the conditions and theories of their making. By examining many forms of cinema, from Hollywood and the international art cinema to the avant-garde, Fischer considers the gender, age, and mental or physical health of fictionalized writers; the dramatized interaction between artists and their audiences and critics; and the formal play of written words and nonverbal images. By analyzing such movies as Adaptation,Diary of a Country Priest, Naked Lunch, American Splendor, and Irezumi, Fischer tracks the parallels between film author and character, looking not for the creative figure who stands outside the text, but for the one who stands within it as corporeal presence and alter-ego.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAuteur theory (Motion pictures) 0aAuteur theory (Motion pictures). 0aAuthors in motion pictures. 0aMotion picture authorship. 0aMotion pictures and literature. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081355450140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813554501423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813554501.jpg  a978-3-11-068861-0  Rutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK